                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d393">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.5294/413: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-12-05T14:00:00+09:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 5, 1923—2 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 5—9:40 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>188. Department’s telegram no. 255, November 23rd. Since publication of Supreme
                    Court decision, agitation in Japanese press concerning Pacific Coast land
                    question, while not violent, has been increasing and a number of Japanese
                    associations interested in emigration have been publicly urging the Foreign
                    Office that, “Owing to the now prevalent sympathy for Japan among American
                    people, moment is opportune for suggesting to the American Government <pb
                        facs="0588" n="464" xml:id="pg_464"/> the appointment of a joint high
                    commission to investigate whole matter.”</p>
                <p>However, no comments have been made at Foreign Office to me on the question.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
